title: Mental Workload in Kanji Transformation Using Semantic Information for the Visually Impaired
title_en: Mental Workload in Kanji Transformation Using Semantic Information for the Visually Impaired
abstract: 本研究は視覚障害者が漢字変換候補を非視覚的手段で確認する際に生じる精神的負荷を扱う研究である。 本研究は文脈に基づく意味情報を用いて漢字変換候補を絞り込み、点字や音声で候補を確認する利用者の負担を軽減する手法を提案する。
abstract_en: This study addresses the mental workload that visually impaired users experience when checking kanji conversion candidates by non-visual means. This study proposes a method that narrows kanji conversion candidates using context-based semantic information to reduce the burden of checking candidates via braille or audio.
positioning_summary: 本研究は視覚障害者の漢字変換における候補確認時の精神的負荷を問題として位置づけている。 本研究は視覚障害者が点字や音声で漢字変換候補を検索・選択する際に負う精神的負荷を主要な課題としている。
positioning_summary_en: This study positions mental workload during kanji conversion for visually impaired users as the central problem. This study identifies the main issue as the mental burden that visually impaired users incur when searching and selecting kanji conversion candidates by braille or audio.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は視覚障害者が漢字変換時に候補一覧の検索と選択で負う精神的負荷を低減することである。 本研究は点字や音声で候補を確認する利用者の負担を軽減することを具体的な目標としている。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to reduce the mental workload that visually impaired users experience when searching and selecting kanji conversion candidates. The purpose of this study specifically aims to lessen the burden on users who check candidates via braille or audio.
method_summary: 本研究は文脈に基づく意味情報を用いて漢字変換候補を絞り込む手法を提案している。 本研究は本システムとして候補の順位付けと絞り込みを行う設計を提示し、文脈に基づく意味情報で候補を制限する仕組みを用いている。
method_summary_en: This study proposes a method that narrows kanji conversion candidates using context-based semantic information. This study presents a system design that ranks and filters candidates, using contextual semantic information to limit candidate sets.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は被験者実験で主観的作業負荷尺度を用いて評価を行い、試行データ990件を基に識別性能を算出する方法を採用した。 本研究は被験者データから識別率85.3%（844/990）および92.0%（911/990）、平均尺度値15.1および10.9、低頻度事象の割合3.0%（30/990）および1.3%（13/990）といった定量結果を報告している。
evaluation_summary_en: This study evaluated the approach using participant experiments with a subjective workload scale and computed classification performance based on 990 trials of trial data. This study reported quantitative results including identification rates of 85.3% (844/990) and 92.0% (911/990), mean scale values of 15.1 and 10.9, and low-frequency event rates of 3.0% (30/990) and 1.3% (13/990).

Title: Mental Workload in Kanji Transformation Using Semantic Information for the Visually Impaired
Authors: Satomi Tanimoto, Masafumi Nishida, Yasuo Horiuchi, Akira Ichikawa
Year: 2007
Abstract: This study addresses the mental workload that visually impaired users experience when checking kanji conversion candidates by non-visual means. This study proposes a method that narrows kanji conversion candidates using context-based semantic information to reduce the burden of checking candidates via braille or audio.
Positioning Summary: This study positions mental workload during kanji conversion for visually impaired users as the central problem. This study identifies the main issue as the mental burden that visually impaired users incur when searching and selecting kanji conversion candidates by braille or audio.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to reduce the mental workload that visually impaired users experience when searching and selecting kanji conversion candidates. The purpose of this study specifically aims to lessen the burden on users who check candidates via braille or audio.
Method Summary: This study proposes a method that narrows kanji conversion candidates using context-based semantic information. This study presents a system design that ranks and filters candidates, using contextual semantic information to limit candidate sets.
Evaluation Summary: This study evaluated the approach using participant experiments with a subjective workload scale and computed classification performance based on 990 trials of trial data. This study reported quantitative results including identification rates of 85.3% (844/990) and 92.0% (911/990), mean scale values of 15.1 and 10.9, and low-frequency event rates of 3.0% (30/990) and 1.3% (13/990).
